RosterBot Installation Guide
============================

Table of Contents
-----------------
1. Requirements
2. Quick Start
3. Configure Options
4. Finding Your Discord User ID
5. Setting Up the Discord Bot Application
6. After Installation
7. Process Manager Notes
8. Upgrading


1. Requirements
---------------
System:
  - Linux (Debian/Ubuntu or RHEL/CentOS/Fedora recommended)
  - Perl 5.020 or newer
  - SQLite 3
  - Root/sudo access for installation

Perl modules:
  - DBI
  - DBD::SQLite
  - Mojolicious (provides Mojo::UserAgent, Mojo::IOLoop, Mojo::JSON)
  - Mail::VRFY
  - Date::Parse (from the TimeDate distribution)

Process manager (one of):
  - systemd  (auto-detected)
  - daemontools (svscan/supervise, softlimit, setuidgid, multilog)
  - SysV init.d

To install missing dependencies:

  sudo sh scripts/install-deps.sh


2. Quick Start
--------------
  # 1. Install dependencies (if needed)
  sudo sh scripts/install-deps.sh

  # 2. Configure -- see section 3 for all options
  ./configure \
      --prefix=/usr/local/rosterbot \
      --process-manager=systemd \
      --admin-username=yourdiscordname \
      --admin-id=YOUR_DISCORD_USER_ID

  # 3. Build (substitutes paths into build/)
  make

  # Optional: syntax-check the built files
  make test

  # 4. Install
  # Root is required only for creating system users and installing service files.
  # If the prefix is owned by your user and the system user already exists,
  # sudo may not be needed.
  make install

  # 5. Set your Discord bot token
  sudo vi /usr/local/rosterbot/etc/.passwd
  # Set: DISCORD_TOKEN=Bot.your.token.here

  # 6. Restart the service to pick up the token
  sudo systemctl restart rosterbot    # systemd
  sudo svc -t /service/rosterbot      # daemontools
  sudo /etc/init.d/rosterbot restart  # init.d


3. Configure Options
--------------------
Run ./configure --help for a full listing. Key options:

  --prefix=DIR
      Root installation directory. All other paths default under here.
      Default: /usr/local/rosterbot

  --bindir=DIR
      Where scripts (rosterbot.pl, export-users.pl) are installed.
      Default: $PREFIX/scripts

  --libdir=DIR
      Where Perl library modules are installed.
      Default: $PREFIX/lib

  --dbdir=DIR
      Where the SQLite database is stored.
      Default: $PREFIX/sql

  --etcdir=DIR
      Where editable config files are installed (contact message, etc.).
      Default: $PREFIX/etc

  --sysconfdir=DIR
      Where the .passwd (Discord token) file lives.
      Default: $PREFIX/etc

  --logdir=DIR
      Log directory (used by daemontools multilog; created for init.d too).
      Default: /var/log/rosterbot

  --process-manager=TYPE
      One of: systemd, daemontools, initd
      Default: auto (tries systemd first, then daemontools, then initd)

  --service-dir=DIR
      Daemontools service scan directory (only for daemontools).
      Default: /service

  --user=USER
      System user to run RosterBot as.
      Default: rosterbot  (created automatically during 'make install')
      NOTE: Running as root is accepted but strongly discouraged.

  --group=GROUP
      System group for the RosterBot user.
      Default: rosterbot

  --log-user=USER
      Daemontools log service user (daemontools only).
      Default: ${USER}l  (e.g., "rosterbotl" when user is "rosterbot")

  --log-group=GROUP
      Group for the log user (daemontools only).
      Default: same as --log-user

  --mem-limit=BYTES
      Maximum memory in bytes for the RosterBot process.
      Default: 314572800  (300 MB)

  --admin-username=NAME
      Discord username of the initial bot administrator.
      Must be paired with --admin-id.
      Can be added later via sqlite3 (see section 6).

  --admin-id=ID
      Discord user ID (numeric snowflake) of the initial bot administrator.
      Must be paired with --admin-username.

  --perl=PATH
      Path to the perl interpreter.
      Default: auto-detected from PATH

  --sqlite3=PATH
      Path to the sqlite3 binary.
      Default: auto-detected from PATH


4. Finding Your Discord User ID
--------------------------------
Discord user IDs are large numeric identifiers (snowflakes), e.g.: 123456789012345678

To find your own user ID:

  a) Open Discord (desktop or web app)
  b) Go to User Settings > Advanced
  c) Enable "Developer Mode"
  d) Close settings
  e) Right-click your own username anywhere in Discord
  f) Select "Copy User ID"

The copied value is your user ID to pass to --admin-id.

To find another user's ID, right-click their username and select "Copy User ID".

Note: User IDs are 17-19 digit numbers. Do not confuse them with usernames.


5. Setting Up the Discord Bot Application
------------------------------------------
Before installing RosterBot, you need a Discord bot application:

  a) Go to https://discord.com/developers/applications
  b) Click "New Application", give it a name (e.g., "RosterBot")
  c) Go to "Bot" in the left sidebar
  d) Click "Reset Token" and copy the token -- you will need this
     for the DISCORD_TOKEN in your .passwd file
  e) Under "Privileged Gateway Intents", enable:
       - Server Members Intent
       - Message Content Intent
  f) Go to OAuth2 > URL Generator:
       - Scopes: bot
       - Bot Permissions: (none required -- leave all unchecked)
     Copy the generated URL and share it with the Discord server owner
     so they can invite the bot to their server.

The bot token goes in $PREFIX/etc/.passwd (default /usr/local/rosterbot/etc/.passwd):

  DISCORD_TOKEN=Bot.your.token.goes.here.exactly.as.copied


6. After Installation
----------------------
a) Verify the bot is running:

   systemctl status rosterbot           # systemd
   svstat /service/rosterbot            # daemontools
   /etc/init.d/rosterbot status         # init.d

b) View logs:

   journalctl -u rosterbot -f           # systemd
   tail -f /var/log/rosterbot/current   # daemontools (multilog format)
   tail -f /var/log/rosterbot/rosterbot.log  # init.d

c) If you did not set --admin-id during configure, add an admin via sqlite3:

   sqlite3 /usr/local/rosterbot/sql/rosterbot.db << 'SQL'
   INSERT OR IGNORE INTO users (user_id, username, contact_status)
     VALUES ('YOUR_DISCORD_ID', 'yourusername', 'provided');
   INSERT OR IGNORE INTO admins (user_id, username, granted_by, granted_at)
     VALUES ('YOUR_DISCORD_ID', 'yourusername', 'YOUR_DISCORD_ID', datetime('now'));
   SQL

   Replace YOUR_DISCORD_ID with your numeric user ID (see section 4).
   Replace yourusername with your Discord username.

   You must restart the bot after modifying the database:

   systemctl restart rosterbot

d) Set persistent runtime options in the config file:

   $PREFIX/etc/rosterbot.conf is installed with all settings commented out:

     debug=1          # verbose debug logging
     no-contact=1     # disable automatic contact requests (maintenance mode)
     notify-only=bob  # route all admin notifications to a single user

   Boolean settings accept: 1, yes, true  (anything else is false).
   CLI flags always override the config file. The file is never overwritten
   during upgrades. Run 'rosterbot.pl --help' for the full flag reference.

f) Customize the contact request message sent to Discord members:

   Edit $PREFIX/etc/contact_message.txt (e.g. /usr/local/rosterbot/etc/contact_message.txt).
   The bot reads this file each time it sends a contact request, so changes
   take effect immediately without restarting. A default message is installed
   automatically and will never be overwritten during upgrades.

   To preview the current message, DM the bot:
     contact print

g) DM the bot "help" in Discord to confirm you have admin access.

h) Generate a server invite link by DMing the bot:

   generate invite

   Share the returned URL with Discord server administrators.

i) Export user data:

   # Text table with email and phone
   /usr/local/rosterbot/scripts/export-users.pl

   # CSV with all fields, only users who provided info
   /usr/local/rosterbot/scripts/export-users.pl \
       --format=csv --all --status=provided

   See: /usr/local/rosterbot/scripts/export-users.pl --help


7. Process Manager Notes
-------------------------
systemd:
  Unit file installed to: /etc/systemd/system/rosterbot.service
  Start:    systemctl start rosterbot
  Stop:     systemctl stop rosterbot
  Restart:  systemctl restart rosterbot
  Logs:     journalctl -u rosterbot

daemontools:
  Service directory: $SERVICE_DIR/rosterbot -> $PREFIX/supervise
  Run script:        $PREFIX/supervise/run
  Log run script:    $PREFIX/supervise/log/run
  Start:    svc -u /service/rosterbot
  Stop:     svc -d /service/rosterbot
  Restart:  svc -t /service/rosterbot
  Status:   svstat /service/rosterbot
  Logs:     tail -f /var/log/rosterbot/current

init.d:
  Script: /etc/init.d/rosterbot
  Start:    /etc/init.d/rosterbot start
  Stop:     /etc/init.d/rosterbot stop
  Restart:  /etc/init.d/rosterbot restart
  Status:   /etc/init.d/rosterbot status
  Logs:     tail -f /var/log/rosterbot/rosterbot.log


8. Upgrading
------------
  # Pull latest source
  git pull

  # Re-run configure with same options (check config.status for previous args)
  # Note: --admin-username and --admin-id are not needed when upgrading;
  #       admins are already in the database.
  ./configure [same options as before]

  # Stop the service
  sudo systemctl stop rosterbot          # systemd
  sudo svc -d /service/rosterbot         # daemontools
  sudo /etc/init.d/rosterbot stop        # init.d

  # Install updated files
  sudo make install

  # The database schema uses IF NOT EXISTS so re-running is safe.
  # contact_message.txt and rosterbot.conf are never overwritten during upgrade.
  # New columns added in upgrades may require manual ALTER TABLE statements
  # -- check the changelog.
